Use MAUI's `#if` platform directives inside `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS`** are predefined compilation constants in MAUI projects — no extra setup needed.
- Each platform-specific class lives under `Platforms/<platform>/` and implements `INotificationService`.
- Only the relevant implementation compiles per target, so there's no runtime risk of missing types.
- If you later add macOS/Tizen, just add another `#elif` branch (or register a stub/no-op fallback in a final `#else`).
